Lab 5 objectives

  • Learn to parse dates with lubridate package

  • One and two-sample t-test (were ahead in lab of where we are in lecture)
  • Create a heatmap with geom_tile()

Use tidyr::uncount() function to convert our lobster data from frequency format to case format

lobster_tidy <- lobster_abundance %>%
  tidyr::uncount(lobster_count)

Exploratory data visualization

Were only going to consider site as our variable of interest

ggplot(lobster_tidy, aes(x = site, y = size_mm)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color = site),
              alpha = 0.5,
              width = 0.2)

Convert date column to class Date

Well use the lubridate package to convert to date format, and then to help us easily parse month and year

lobster_date <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  mutate(
    date_new = lubridate::mdy(date)
  )

Now lets parse year and month using lubridate::month() and lubridate::year()

lobster_parse_date <- lobster_date %>% 
  mutate(
    obs_month = lubridate::month(date_new, label = TRUE),
    obs_year = lubridate::year(date_new)
  )

Now lets find counts of observed lobsters based on different hierarchical groupings.

First, lets count lobsters by year and month.

lobster_ym <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  dplyr::count(obs_year, obs_month)

lobster_y <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  dplyr::count(obs_year)

lobster_site <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  dplyr::count(site)

lobster_site
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   site      n
##   <chr> <int>
## 1 AQUE    422
## 2 CARP   1619
## 3 IVEE   2304
## 4 MOHK    982
## 5 NAPL   1039

If we want to create a summary table that contains statistics other than counts by group, its easier to use group_by() plus the n() function

lobster_summary <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  group_by(site) %>% 
  summarize(
    mean_size = mean(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_size = sd(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
    lobster_number = n()
  )

lobster_summary
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
##   site  mean_size sd_size lobster_number

Two-sample t-test to compare means

We want to ask: Is there a significant difference in lobster lengths at Naples and Mohawk reefs?

Weve done our necessary exploratory analyses to determine that a two-sample t-test for means comparison is appropriate.

napl_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "NAPL") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

mohk_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "MOHK") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

mn_ttest <- t.test(mohk_sample, napl_sample)

mn_ttest
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mohk_sample and napl_sample
## t = -19.849, df = 1850.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -12.43436 -10.19806
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  66.86833  78.18454

There is a significant difference in lobster lengths between Naples and Mohawk Reef (t(df) = statistic, p < 0.001, alpha = 0.05). (This should always be the least interesting part of a description of data. More interesting? What are the actual means, whats the structure of the data, etc.)

lobster_mn <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site %in% c("NAPL", "MOHK"))

mn_ttest2 <- t.test(size_mm ~site, data = lobster_mn)

mn_ttest2
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  size_mm by site
## t = -19.849, df = 1850.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -12.43436 -10.19806
## sample estimates:
## mean in group MOHK mean in group NAPL 
##           66.86833           78.18454
mn_ttest2$p.value
## [1] 1.215408e-79
mn_ttest2$statistic
##         t 
## -19.84873

Here is the p-value: 1.215407810^{-79}

Here is my t-statistic: -19.8487322

Both of those sentences are bad ways of talking about stats but are serving to show how to format so that the stat values will auto-update

lobster_ys <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  count(obs_year, site)


ggplot(data = lobster_ys, aes(x = obs_year, y = site)) +
  geom_tile(aes(fill = n))
